{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dac26703-0e9a-4054-87e2-41e45fca909a","content":"# Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the MCP Inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`) that:\n\n1. **Spawns your server** as a child process using stdio\n2. **Lists tools/resources** — click \"List Tools\" to verify registration\n3. **Lets you invoke tools** — fill in parameters and call them interactively\n4. **Shows raw JSON-RPC** messages in both directions for debugging\n\n### Tips\n\n- If your server needs arguments, append them after `--`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer -- --some-flag\n  ```\n- Set environment variables with `-e`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e KEY=value dotnet run ...\n  ```\n- Check the **Messages** tab to inspect the full protocol exchange if a tool call fails.\n- If your server writes logs to stderr, they'll appear in the Inspector's console output (stdio transport reserves stdout for JSON-RPC).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"391f2946-7ac6-4aba-aaa9-791702401a19","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling - I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":356,"requestId":"2C03:247AEF:2A47916:2EA3FA7:69FD3672"},"id":"04482ee5-658e-40bb-959c-149c90d7ac8c","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:03:56.948Z","parentId":"537d384f-4fd8-45ef-9cc0-87555b8d9ddf"}
